[[File:Hubert_Schiffer_&_Robert_Lewis.jpg|thumb|right|Schiffer (left) with ''[[Enola Gay]]'' co-pilot [[Robert A. Lewis]] in 1951]]
'''Father Hubert F. Schiffer, S.J.''' (1915 in [[Gütersloh]] – March 27, 1982 in [[Frankfurt]], [[West Germany]])<ref name=Myers>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/12370089/miamian_who_dropped_bomb/ |title=Miamian who dropped bomb |first=Donald P. |last=Myers |newspaper=[[The Miami News]] |date=August 6, 1982 |accessdate=July 14, 2017 |via=newspapers.com}}</ref>{{ref|DOD|note}} was a [[Germans|German]] [[Jesuit]] who survived the [[nuclear weapon|atomic bomb]] "[[Little Boy]]" dropped on [[Hiroshima]].

==Hiroshima bombing==
Schiffer was one of several Jesuit priests who were at their [[Mission (station)|mission]] compound, less than {{convert|1|mi|km}} from [[ground zero]] when the [[Atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki|explosion occurred]].

;Jesuits and their location
Many retellings of the event state there were eight Jesuit priests (or [[Missionary|missionaries]]), who were eight blocks from ground zero.<ref name=RosaryAd>{{cite newspaper |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/12387493/rosary_miracle_at_hiroshima/ |title=Rosary Miracle at Hiroshima (advertisement) |newspaper=[[The News Journal]] |location=[[Wilmington, Delaware]] |date=March 19, 2011 |accessdate=July 15, 2017 |via=newspapers.com}}</ref><ref name=holysouls>{{cite web |url=http://holysouls.com/sar/rosarymiracle.htm |title=Rosary Miracle - Safe in the Midst of Hiroshima Nuclear Blast !! |date=February 2000 |first=Stephen |last=Rinehart}}</ref> [[John Hersey]], in his contemporary 1946 account ''[[Hiroshima (book)|Hiroshima]]'', lists four Jesuit priests (Father Superior LaSalle [sic], Father Wilhelm Kleinsorge, Father Cieslik, and Father Schiffer) and places them {{convert|1400|yd|m}} "from the center."<ref name=Hersey/> Schiffer himself states there were four Jesuit priests — "Father [[Hugo Enomiya-Lassalle|Hugo Lassalle]], Superior of the whole Jesuit Mission in Japan, and Fathers Kleinsorge, Cieslik, and Schiffer" — and describes his own location as "within the most deadly one-mile radius."<ref name=Rosary/> Schiffer also notes the name of their church — "the Jesuit Church of Our Lady's Assumption."<ref name=Rosary/>

;Explosion
According to the 1946 account of Jesuit priest Father John Siemes, who had been on the outskirts of the city:
{{quote|They were in their rooms at the Parish House—it was a quarter after eight, exactly the time when we had heard the explosion in Nagatsuke—when came the intense light and immediately thereafter the sound of breaking windows, walls and furniture. They were showered with glass splinters and fragments of wreckage. Father Schiffer was buried beneath a portion of a wall and suffered a severe head injury. The Father Superior received most of the splinters in his back and lower extremity from which he bled copiously. Everything was thrown about in the rooms themselves, but the wooden framework of the house remained intact.<ref name=Siemes>{{cite journal |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SAwAAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA3&pg=PA1 |journal=Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists |title=Hiroshima—August 6, 1945 |first=John |last=Siemes |date=May 15, 1946 |volume=1 |number=11 |pp=2–6 |via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref>}}

Schiffer's own account describes the explosion:
{{quote|Suddenly, a terrific explosion filled the air with one bursting thunderstroke. An invisible force lifted me from the chair, hurled me through the air, shook me, battered me, whirled me 'round and 'round like a leaf in a gust of autumn wind.<ref name=Rosary>{{cite web |url=http://digitalcommons.sacredheart.edu/library_specialcollections/2/ |title=The Rosary Of Hiroshima |first=Hubert F. |last=Schiffer |date=1953 |website=[[Sacred Heart University]]}}</ref>}}

;Survivors
All four Jesuit priests survived the explosion.<ref name=Rosary/> Quoted in 1950, Schiffer said, "Of 14 clergy and [[Laity|laymen]] we lost only one, a Japanese."<ref name=PI1950>{{cite newspaper |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/12387872/hiroshima_victim_here_describes_atom/ |title=Hiroshima Victim Here, Describes Atom Horrors |newspaper=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]] |date=March 8, 1950 |accessdate=July 15, 2017 |via=newspapers.com}}</ref> The Jesuits were in a building stronger than most surrounding buildings, as noted by Hersey and Siemes, respectively:
{{quote|sign=|source=|[Father Kleinsorge saw] that all the buildings round about had fallen down except the Jesuits’ mission house, which had long before been braced and double-braced by a priest named Gropper, who was terrified of earthquakes<ref name=Hersey>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/1946/08/31/hiroshima |title=Hiroshima |first=John |last=Hersey |magazine=[[The New Yorker]] |date=August 31, 1946 |author-link=John Hersey}}</ref>}}
{{quote|sign=|source=|The solidity of the structure which was the work of Brother Gropper again shone forth.<ref name=Siemes/>}}
They were not the only survivors close to ground zero; an estimated 14% of people within {{convert|1|km|mi}} of ground zero survived the explosion.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hiroshima-remembered.com/maps/HiroshimaMap.html |title=Atomic Bomb Damage of Hiroshima |website=Hiroshima & Nagasaki Remembered}}</ref> Other survivors included ten people in a streetcar {{convert|750|m|yd}} from ground zero, and a woman in a bank {{convert|260|m|yd}} away from the blast.<ref name="hibakusha">{{cite web |url=http://www.atomicarchive.com/History/twocities/hiroshima/page14.shtml |title=The Story of Hiroshima, Hibakusha Stories |website=atomicarchive.com}}</ref> One person survived at a distance of just {{convert|170|m|yd}}, protected in the basement of a building while looking for documents.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pcf.city.hiroshima.jp/virtual/VirtualMuseum_e/exhibit_e/exh0203_e/exh02033_e.html |title=Hiroshima Testimony: Special Exhibit 3 |website=Hiroshima Peace Memorial Museum Special Exhibition}}</ref>

;Religious aspects
The survival of the priests has sometimes been referred to as a [[miracle]].<ref name=RosaryAd/><ref name=holysouls/> In 1951, Schiffer said:
{{quote|sign=|source=|I won't call it a miracle exactly, but I think we were under the special protection of God.<ref>{{cite newspaper |url=http://cdm16313.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/LMNP01/id/22051 |title=A-Bombed Priest Final Forum Speaker Tuesday |newspaper=The Loyola Maroon |location=[[New Orleans]] |pp=1, 6 |date=May 11, 1951 |accessdate=July 15, 2017}}</ref>}}
Similarities with [[Nagasaki]] are sometimes highlighted, where a [[Franciscan]] [[friary]] established by St. [[Maximilian Kolbe]] was "unaffected by the bomb which fell there",<ref name=CH/> as "the friary was protected from the force of the bomb by an intervening mountain".<ref name=CH>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.catholicherald.co.uk/commentandblogs/2015/08/09/the-priests-who-survived-the-atomic-bomb/ |title=The priests who survived the atomic bomb |magazine=[[The Catholic Herald]] |first=Donal Anthony |last=Foley |date=August 9, 2015 |accessdate=July 15, 2017}}</ref>

==Later life==
Schiffer met both the pilot and co-pilot of the [[Boeing B-29 Superfortress|B-29]] that bombed Hiroshima, the ''[[Enola Gay]]''. In [[New York City]] in 1951, Schiffer met co-pilot [[Robert A. Lewis]].<ref name=TCA>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/12345288/enola_gay_pilot_hears_bombs_amazing/ |title='Enola Gay' Pilot Hears Bomb's Amazing Effect |newspaper=The Catholic Advance |location=[[Wichita, Kansas]] |date=January 19, 1951 |accessdate=July 13, 2017 |via=newspapers.com}}</ref> Schiffer invited Lewis to visit Hiroshima in August 1952 for the dedication of a "palace of prayer", which Lewis accepted;<ref name=TCA/> however, there is no record of Lewis actually making such a visit. The two also appeared together at [[Fordham University]] in 1957, on the twelfth anniversary of the bombing, with Schiffer noting that they had become "very fast friends."<ref name=ADS>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/12345447/old_pals_differ_on_using_bomb/ |title=Old Pals Differ On Using Bomb |newspaper=[[Arizona Daily Star]] |location=[[Tucson, Arizona]] |agency=[[Associated Press|AP]] |date=August 7, 1957 |accessdate=July 13, 2017 |via=newspapers.com}}</ref> Schiffer later met pilot [[Paul Tibbets]] in [[Dallas]] in 1975.<ref name=Myers/>

Schiffer, who had received a [[bachelor's degree]] in Japan, received a [[master's degree]] from Fordham University in 1952, and a [[Doctor of Philosophy|doctorate]] there in 1958.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://archive.org/stream/generalbull195961loyo/generalbull195961loyo_djvu.txt |title=General Information Bulletin |publisher=[[Loyola University New Orleans|Loyola University]] |location=[[New Orleans]] |date=December 1958 |accessdate=July 15, 2017 |via=archive.org}}</ref> In the 1960s, Schiffer worked as an [[associate professor]] of economics at [[Saint Joseph's University|St. Joseph's College]] in [[Philadelphia]],<ref>{{cite newspaper |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/12390727/sodality_to_hear_talk_by_survivor_of/ |title=Sodality to Hear Talk By Survivor of A-Bomb |newspaper=[[Delaware County Daily Times]] |location=[[Chester, Pennsylvania]] |date=September 29, 1961 |accessdate=July 15, 2017 |via=newspapers.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/12390522/speaker_schiffer/ |title=Speaker |newspaper=The Bristol Daily Courier |location=[[Bristol, Pennsylvania]] |date=December 5, 1961 |accessdate=July 15, 2017 |via=newspapers.com}}</ref> and wrote a book on the Japanese banking system.


